        <section aria-labelledby="how-to-use-lifestyle-heading" class="prose">
          <h2 id="how-to-use-lifestyle-heading">How to use Lifestyle & Everyday calculators effectively</h2>
          <p>
            Lifestyle tools are most useful when they turn vague ideas (“I should save more”, “I’m always busy”)
            into concrete numbers you can act on. A simple workflow:
          </p>
          <ol>
            <li><strong>Pick one area to improve this week</strong> – time, money, health, hobbies, or travel.</li>
            <li><strong>Quantify your baseline</strong> – use a calculator to measure where you are now.</li>
            <li><strong>Set a realistic target</strong> – e.g. 30 minutes more sleep, $5 less per day, 2k extra steps.</li>
            <li><strong>Re‑calculate after a few days</strong> to see if your routine is moving in the right direction.</li>
          </ol>

          <h3>Example: balancing time, money, and movement in a day</h3>
          <p>
            The mini planner at the top of this page gives a quick snapshot. Behind the scenes it uses simple,
            transparent calculations:
          </p>

          <div class="formula-box text-sm">
            <p><strong>1. Free time per day</strong></p>
            <p>
              Total hours in a day: \(24\)<br>
              Sleep hours: \(S\)<br>
              Work/study hours: \(W\)
            </p>
            <p>
              <code>free_time = 24 − S − W</code>
            </p>
            <p><strong>2. Budget usage</strong></p>
            <p>
              Daily budget: \(B\)<br>
              Planned spend: \(P\)
            </p>
            <p>
              <code>spend_ratio = P / B</code> (if \(B &gt; 0\))<br>
              <code>leftover = B − P</code>
            </p>
            <p><strong>3. Steps progress</strong></p>
            <p>
              Steps goal: \(G\)<br>
              Planned steps: \(T\)
            </p>
            <p>
              <code>steps_ratio = T / G</code> (if \(G &gt; 0\))
            </p>
          </div>

          <p>
            These simple ratios are enough to answer questions like:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>“Do I actually have free time today, or am I over‑committed?”</li>
            <li>“Is this outing within my daily budget?”</li>
            <li>“Will my planned walk hit my step goal?”</li>
          </ul>

          <h3>Tips for building better everyday routines</h3>
          <ul>
